Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Director of Equity, Diversity &amp; Inclusion (Permanent, Full time) Burnaby , BC Description Who We AreSFU’s libraries are sites of inspiration and creation, as well as access to information. Library facilities on all three campuses provide access to collections, research assistance, equipment loans, and study space. Members of our 170-person workforce are student-centered, service-oriented, and critical partners in research and knowledge creation. Library employees drive our success. We work together to create a positive environment for library users and a thriving and sustainable work environment for employees. Our work centers five priority approaches outlined in the library’s strategic plan for 2022-2024: Relationships &amp; Community; Reconciliation and Decolonization; Equity; Climate Action; and Evidence-Informed Decision Making.About the RoleThe Director, Equity, Diversity and Inclusion (EDI) develops and facilitates best practices and services in the area of EDI, in collaboration with all divisions of the SFU library. The role acts as a central resource, providing advice and support, and develops and implements equity and inclusion initiatives for library staff and faculty, as well as recommending changes to increase inclusion in library services to students and scholars. Reporting to the Dean of Libraries, the Director works closely with the supervisor, Associate Deans and library Division Heads to provide leadership for equity initiatives in the library’s three campus locations. The role participates as a member of the university’s EDI community of practice, and coordinates with equity initiatives in other university units as appropriate.Full Job DescriptionQualificationsBachelor's degree in Equity Studies, Sociology, Organizational Behaviour, Human Resources or in a relevant discipline, and five years of related experience working in libraries and/or higher education, developing and implementing equity and inclusion initiatives and experience coaching and supporting leaders and managers. Excellent communication skills and commitment to work from an anti-oppression perspective.Ability to facilitate and participate in challenging conversations in difficult contexts.Ability to work effectively and build trust within diverse groups.Ability to lead change, especially through collaboration and consensus building.Ability to analyze and evaluate processes and programs to create innovative and strategic improvements.What We OfferAt SFU, our goal is to ensure our people are valued and supported by promoting a healthy work-life balance, professional growth and development, as well as a safe and respectful workplace. We offer continuing employees who belong in the Administrative &amp; Professional Staff Association (APSA):4 weeks’ vacation (prorated for the first year)*Hybrid-work program for eligible positionsEmployer paid defined benefit pension planOn-campus tuition waiver for employees and their immediate family members*Off-campus tuition reimbursements and professional development funds*And more! View our benefits brochure*Prorated for part-time employeesAdditional InformationPlease include your cover letter and resume in one attachment.Apply to https://tre.tbe.taleo.net/tre01/ats/careers/v2/app...We are committed to ensuring that the application and interview process is accessible to all applicants. If you require any assistance or accommodations, please contact human_resources@sfu.ca.Simon Fraser University is committed to the principle of Employment Equity.For questions or assistance with this posting contact human_resources@sfu.ca Compensation $94,369 to $112,691 Annually Closes: 30 May, 2023 Simon Fraser University - Library Burnaby , BC Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
